<p><b>501(c)</b> is a provision of the United States <a href="/wiki/Internal_Revenue_Code" title="Internal Revenue Code">Internal Revenue Code</a> (<a href="/wiki/Internal_Revenue_Code" title="Internal Revenue Code">26 U.S.C.</a>&#160;<a href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/26/501(c).html" class="external text" title="http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/26/501(c).html" rel="nofollow">§&#160;501(c)</a>), listing 26 types of <a href="/wiki/Non-profit_organization" title="Non-profit organization">non-profit organizations</a> <a href="/wiki/Tax_exemption" title="Tax exemption">exempt</a> from some <a href="/wiki/Taxation_in_the_United_States" title="Taxation in the United States">federal</a> <a href="/wiki/Income_tax_in_the_United_States" title="Income tax in the United States">income taxes</a>. Sections 503 through 505 list the requirements for attaining such exemptions. Many states reference Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.</p>
